Title : Pietro di Miniato
Text : {{Orphan|date=April 2014}}

'''Pietro di Miniato''' or '''Pietro di San Miniato''' (c. 1366 - 1430-46) was an [[Italy|Italian]] painter, active in [[Florence]] and [[Prato]], in a [[Gothic Art|Gothic]] style.<ref>[http://www.philamuseum.org/collections/permanent/51440.html?mulR=605 Philadelphia Museum of Art], ''Crucifixion with the Mourning Virgin and St John the Evangelist'' (c. 1420), tempera on wood, attributed to Pietro di Miniato.</ref> He collaborated with a relative Antonio di Miniato di Piero, likely his son, active circa 1430 in and around Prato.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=-gJ9hRZbNHwC Calendario pratese del 1650, Memorie e Studi], by Raneiri Guasti, page 105.</ref> Among the works attributed to him are a painted crucifix in the [[St Louis Museum of Art]],<ref>[http://fe.fondazionezeri.unibo.it/catalogo/scheda.jsp?decorator=layout_S2&apply=true&tipo_scheda=OA&id=5524&titolo=Pietro+di+Miniato%0a%09%09%09%0a%09%09+++++%2c+Cristo+crocifisso Fondazione Zeri] archive, referencing work in St Louis.</ref><ref>[http://www.slam.org/emuseum/code/emuseum.asp?style=Browse&currentrecord=109&page=collection&profile=objects&searchdesc=European%20Art...&newvalues=1&newstyle=single&newcurrentrecord=113 St Louis Museum of Art], crucifix.</ref> a [[polyptych]] in the [[Museo Civico of Prato]], a painted mural in the church of San Niccol√≤ da Bari in Prato, and a mural in the Chapel of San Stefano of the [[Duomo di Prato]], depicting the Virgin and child flanked by saints.<ref>[http://www.piccoligrandimusei.it/OperaDuomoPratoOpere.phtml Piccoli, Grandi Musei di Italia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427204405/http://www.piccoligrandimusei.it/OperaDuomoPratoOpere.phtml |date=2014-04-27 }}, Works in the Museo dell'Opera del Duomo di Prato.</ref>
[[File:Pietro di miniato, martirio di s. sebastiano.JPG|thumb|Partial fresco depicting ''Martyrdom of St Sebastian'' in [[Sant'Ambrogio, Florence]]]] An ''Annunciation'' in [[Santa Maria Novella, Florence]], long unattributed, is now identified as the work of Pietro di Miniato. 

